\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *179}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Those axioms are implicit for most of us, and, as this Article and our next illuminate, they define the starting points for most scholars and }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber61}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber61}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 policymakers.  Indeed, neoclassical economists have built their theory around a formal version of those basic axioms.  According to conventional economic assumptions, a person's preferences can be inferred from that person's choices--the latter reveal the former. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B196}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B196}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F196 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN196]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   As illustrated in this Article and its companion, the starting points of dominant legal theories are unrealistic and are based on fundamentally inaccurate visions of humanity.}\par 
