III. A Brief Introduction to Critical Realism}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     [T]he search was on, from World War II onwards, for a new method to replace the deductive approach of the late nineteenth century with some criterion for judicial lawmaking other than open-ended, contextualized policy analysis, one that would be plausibly non-political.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  --Duncan Kennedy }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B197}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B197}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F197 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN197]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     The life of the law has not been logic: it has been experience.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  --Oliver Wendell Holmes }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B198}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B198}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F198 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN198]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  In light of evidence about how real humans actually behave, most conventional legal theories, which are based primarily on dispositionist premises, seem suspect.  By way of an alternative, therefore, this Section introduces critical realism--the legal theoretic approach hinted at above, named and cursorily defined here, and employed in this Article and in others to follow. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B199}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B199}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F199 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN199]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Because terms like "critical" and "realism" have been widely used to describe }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber62}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber62}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 a variety of legal-theoretic approaches, and because they have been infused with a variety of meanings, we begin by offering a loose, simple explanation of what we hope to capture by the phrase "critical realism." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B200}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B200}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F200 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN200]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
}{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *181}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  A. "Realism"}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  By "realism" we mean, first, to suggest that our approach is a descendent of American legal realism and to claim allegiance to the basic assumptions and attitudes that its other descendents, including law and economics }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B201}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B201}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F201 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN201]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  and law and society, claim.  The theoretical foundation of the legal realist tradition includes "a 'scientific outlook' that posits a knowable world out there beyond the text, a world whose workings are not transparent and which invite exploration to discern their deeper and truer contours." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B202}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B202}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F202 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN202]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  This tradition of realism has been driven by the desire to "explain legal realities" through a commitment to the belief that "legal scholarship (and law) will be enriched by the application of science." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B203}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B203}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F203 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN203]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   The "science" of this tradition is a social science, for the realist is committed to the consequentialist belief that "the meaning of law resides in its effects on human well-being (variously conceived) }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *182}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  rather than in its formal characteristics." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B204}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B204}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F204 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN204]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Perhaps most import-antly, legal realists believe that their task is not only important, but promising; the history of realism has been advanced under "a conviction that knowledge derived from [its] }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber63}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber63}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 undertaking can promote greater felicity by modifying social arrangements." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B205}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B205}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F205 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN205]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   We will return to this discussion of realism, but we first want to briefly explain the "critical" side of critical realism.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
B. "Critical"}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  By "critical," we mean to suggest that our theory is also a descendent of critical legal studies and other post-modern approaches to law, such as feminist legal theory and critical race theory. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B206}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B206}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F206 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN206]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   To be critical, we believe, means to have (as we do) serious reservations about how "knowable" our world is, about the existence of truly neutral, apolitical social sciences and legal doctrines, and about the independence of judges, scholars, and other reputedly neutral actors and institutions from the influence of existing allocations of power.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  We do not see any necessary contradiction between the "realism" leg and the "critical" leg of our approach, and it is in part our belief that a successful legal theory must stand on both legs that motivates this project. Social scientists are never free from the deep biases that shadow human thinking, and they should therefore be continually self-critical and suspicious of the "knowledge" they produce.  Nevertheless, social science done well can help us understand those biases and limitations, and, in turn, their influence over our theories and institutions.  Such insights can assist us in better }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber64}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber64}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 understanding our social arrangements and in improving overall well-being.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Holmes believed that the life of the law is experience, and so it may be, but to make sense of and to guide that life, legal scholars, among others, should be skeptical of how that experience is construed.  Legal analysis, in other words, should begin with a critical examination of our experience and our perceptions of that experience.  So critical realism is dedicated to gaining knowledge }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *183}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  about our world through scientific inquiry and theoretical analysis, while simultaneously seeking to unearth and understand the myriad biases that render suspicious the "knowledge" that our inquiries and theories produce. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B207}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B207}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F207 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN207]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
C. What Is So Critical About Realism? }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     We have been moving in a direction in which we have an increasingly limited control over our own lives, and that movement has been nourished by a series of arguments which, quite simply, are untrue.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  --Milton Friedman }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B208}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B208}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F208 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN208]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  With that, we can describe a second, even more important facet of what we mean by "critical realism."  For reasons that were suggested above and will become more evident below, we believe that, to best promote human understanding and well-being, legal theories must be anchored in a reality-based understanding of human thinking and behavior.  Realism, we think, is critical. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber65}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber65}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 To be realists, on this telling, means to begin with real humans and to build models from there, rather than to begin with models and then view and interpret humans through them.  The distinction may be better understood by contrasting our approach with what we do not mean by realism, and by describing and distinguishing among the quasi-realistic commitments that some legal scholars have recently made.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  In a related article, we detail the justifications that economists offer for dispositionism in economics and the extent to which economic and legal-economic theorists have, in the name of realism, begun to relax some of the traditional assumptions behind the basic rational actor model. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B209}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B209}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F209 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN209]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   As we conclude in that article, there is no compelling justification for the various shades of unrealism of economics and law and economics, which are more or less premised }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *184}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  on the same fundamental attribution error that distorts all human reasoning. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B210}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B210}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F210 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN210]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   In this Article, we want to focus briefly on just one of the more common justifications offered for eschewing a realistic account of the human animal.  It seems that a key reason why legal economists have been so unwilling to get real about human nature has to do with a somewhat amorphous, but nonetheless powerful fear, that realism is dangerous.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  1. Facing Our Fears of Reality}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  For example, in an article devoted to considering the implications of cognitive psychology for existing products liability laws, Professors Henderson }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber66}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber66}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 and Rachlinski generally assume that consumers are dispositional, if cognitively biased, actors.  However, they con-clude their article by briefly acknowledging the possibility that stable preferences may not in fact underlie consumer "choices": }\par 
