  According to social psychologists, the ultimate divergence in the commitment to dispositionist explanations is a product of the difference in the two cultures' lay theories of the relationship between individuals and society. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B442}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B442}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F442 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN442]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   In the West, the perceptual foundation of the fundamental attribution error is surrounded by lay }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *258}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  theories of the self as an autonomous, free, dispositionally stable individual. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B443}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B443}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F443 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN443]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   In this fashion, the fundamental attribution error serves to confirm the dispositional worldview for Westerners.  On the other hand, cultures in the East entertain lay theories that portray the individual as situated in an array of }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber143}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber143}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 interdependent social relationships in which roles, rather than individual actors, are emphasized. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B444}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B444}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F444 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN444]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Social psychologists, thus, attribute to culture the fact that Eastern subjects appear to correct more easily for the fundamental attribution errors received from basic perceptual cues than do Western subjects. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B445}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B445}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F445 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN445]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   That explanation finds support in a number of cross-cultural studies.  For instance, individuals who have been "multiply enculturated"--that is, exposed extensively to two or more cultures--can be situationally primed to activate the causal schemas characteristic of either culture.  In one study, students in Hong Kong were shown one of the following: Western images (such as a cowboy on a horse), Eastern images (such as a dragon), or neutral images (such as a landscape). }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B446}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B446}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F446 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN446]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Afterwards, when making causal attributions, subjects in the first group were most dispositionist, subjects in the second group were most situationist, and those in the control group fell in between. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B447}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B447}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F447 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN447]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Studies by developmental psychologists have found that Eastern and Western children exhibit common fundamental attribution errors and, unlike their parents, Eastern children do not correct for those errors when situational constraints }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *259}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  are highlighted. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B448}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B448}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F448 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN448]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Having not yet learned the situational lay-theories that their culture provides, their perceptions appear to rest on the limitations that give rise to the fundamental attribution error in Easterners and Westerners alike. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B449}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B449}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F449 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN449]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
