  Marketing and advertising practices thus reveal the deep, though apparently unseen, irony in the advertisements that we summarized earlier. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B469}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B469}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F469 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN469]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Advertisers commonly present to us a vision of ourselves that confirms our self-affirming, dispositionist (and non-manipulable) self-image. They do so, it would seem, in order to manipulate our perceptions and behavior.  The manipulation apparently works, as revealed by their choice to continue doing so at a substantial cost.}\par 
