  In a way, that is our entire case in a nutshell.  We are subject to influence and manipulation from sources that we do not see or do }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *264}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  not consider relevant.  Those with the ability to influence those sources wield immense influence over us, while we continue to believe that we are acting }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber149}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber149}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 independently, according to our preferences.  We conclude that advertising works, but deny that it works on us. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B470}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B470}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F470 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN470]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   But, to borrow one of the oldest strategies in the book, do not take our word for it--listen to what those in the industry say about what they do.  For example, the Web site for Burson-Marsteller, a public relations firm, has this to say about their industry: }\par 
