  --Frederick Douglass }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B638}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B638}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F638 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN638]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Let us return to the topic of slavery. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B639}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B639}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F639 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN639]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   When plantation owners traded in human beings, they were confronted with a problem not }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *309}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  unlike the one faced by the teachers in Milgram's experiment.  In antebellum America, plantation owners and slave traders, among many others, exploited slaves for }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber205}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber205}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 financial and social gain, while maintaining their own perception of themselves as the sort of people who would never unjustly exploit others. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B640}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B640}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F640 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN640]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   All who were more or less complicit with the practices and systems of slavery needed to believe that the groups and systems to which they belonged were fair and just, and somehow not in tension with the principles of equality to which so many subscribed. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B641}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B641}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F641 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN641]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qc \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
a. The basic message--dispositionism}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Faced with this situation, the plantation owners did what we all tend to do--and what most of us in their situation would likely have done at that time.  They looked at their social world and inferred dispositionist distinctions that made slavery not only palatable, but natural, just, and in effect, Pareto superior.  They embraced the self-affirming faith that their captives were intended (by God or nature) to be slaves, and that for their own good they needed to be slaves. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B642}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B642}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F642 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN642]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   It was the plantation owners that were }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *310}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  designed to be the masters, that could tame, train, and protect the slaves from themselves. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B643}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B643}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F643 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN643]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   They found ways to believe that slavery was precisely what slaves preferred--for if a person sings, smiles, and otherwise behaves "as if" she is happy, who can deny that she is? }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B644}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B644}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F644 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN644]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  And if the slaves were not outwardly happy, there was still no good reason to conclude that they were unhappy.  As Elizabeth Cady Stanton summarized: }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber206}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber206}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     It is impossible to make the Southern planter believe that his slave feels and reasons just as he does--that injustice and subjection are as galling as to him--that the degradation of living by the will of another, the mere dependent on his caprice, at the mercy of his passions, is as keenly felt by him as his master.  If you can force on his unwilling vision a vivid picture of the negro's wrongs, and for a moment touch his soul, his logic brings him instant consolation. He says, the slave does not feel this as I would. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B645}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B645}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F645 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN645]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Put differently, slaveowners (and, to some extent, most of antebellum society) }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B646}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B646}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F646 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN646]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  inferred dispositional qualities about the slaves when they considered the situation of American slavery.  They compared those qualities with their views of their own dispositions and concluded that the African race was dispositionally inferior in almost every way.  This subsection will attempt to describe some of the manifestations of that fundamental attribution error-- missing the situation--in this human tragedy.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  i. Revealed inferiority}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  The primary, and perhaps most powerful, tendency of those who defended or were complicit with slavery was to see Africans in America as a subhuman species, or at least as less-highly evolved humans. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B647}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B647}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F647 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN647]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   The truth of the African slaves' inferiority was so obvious }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *311}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  as to usually be beyond debate.  As Chief Justice Taney put it in the infamous Dred Scott decision: }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber207}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber207}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     [Blacks] had for more than a century before been regarded as beings of an inferior order, and altogether unfit to associate with the white race, either in social or political relations; and so far inferior, that they had no rights which the white man was bound to respect; and that the negro might justly and lawfully be reduced to slavery for his benefit.  He was bought and sold, and treated as an ordinary article of merchandise and traffic, whenever a profit could be made by it.  This opinion was at that time fixed and universal in the civilized portion of the white race.  It was regarded as an axiom in morals as well as in politics, which no one thought of disputing, or supposed to be open to dispute; and men in every grade and position in society daily and habitually acted upon it in their private pursuits, as well as in matters of public concern, without doubting for a moment the correctness of this opinion. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B648}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B648}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F648 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN648]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  The consequence of this dispositionist assessment of blacks was staggering.  There were two principle holdings in Dred Scott.  First, it meant that no African could be a citizen of the United States or even of any state "within the meaning of the Constitution." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B649}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B649}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F649 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN649]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Second, because blacks were not citizens in the eyes of the law, they could be treated as any other kind of property.  According to the Court, Congress had no power to treat slaves differently from any other types of property. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B650}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B650}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F650 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN650]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Consequently, the Court held, Congress could not exclude slavery from the federal }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber208}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber208}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 territories, and therefore, that the Missouri Compromise was unconstitutional. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B651}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B651}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F651 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN651]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   But of course, the }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *312}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Court's holding in Dred Scott was considered common sense in much of America at that time. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B652}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B652}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F652 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN652]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   We all see dispositionally, and this dispositionism had long made people blind to the situation of slavery, and to the situational influence on slaves. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B653}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B653}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F653 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN653]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Yet this common sense dispositionist presumption about Africans had not always been the common sense.  In fact, the dispositionism emerged in America precisely because it was needed, as indicated above, }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B654}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B654}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F654 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN654]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  to reconcile principles with practices. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B655}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B655}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F655 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN655]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   And few people, we suspect, felt the dissonance and the need to reconcile more intensely than did Thomas Jefferson }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B656}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B656}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F656 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN656]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 --civil rights theorist, father of the American Revolution, author of the Declaration of Independence, President of the United States, and Virginian slaveholder. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B657}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B657}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F657 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN657]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Indeed, }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *313}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Jefferson presumed to analyze the inherent nature of slaves' inferiority through a neutral and scientific approach.  In an extended argument in his Notes on the State of Virginia, Jefferson enumerated in remarkably dispositionist terms the evidence that he found to justify the maintenance of slavery. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B658}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B658}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F658 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN658]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   We quote him here at length, not only because his analysis is so revealing, but also because it is his analysis, the careful work of a man whose desire for a shared freedom for all men is so celebrated in our culture: }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B659}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B659}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F659 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN659]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     The first difference which strikes us is that of colour. . . . Is it not }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber209}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber209}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 the foundation of a greater or less share of beauty in the two races?  Are not the fine mixtures of red and white, the expressions of every passion by greater or less suffusions of color in the one, preferable to that eternal monotony, which reigns in the countenances, that immoveable veil of black which covers all the emotions of the other race?  Add to these, flowing hair, a more elegant symmetry of form, their own judgment in favour of the whites, declared by their preference of them, as uniformly as is the preference of the Oranootan for the black women over those of his own species. . . . A black, after hard labour through the day, will be induced by the slightest amusements to sit up till midnight, or later, though knowing he must be out with the first dawn of the morning.  They are at least as brave, and more adventuresome.  But this may perhaps proceed from a want of forethought, which prevents their seeing a danger till it be present.  When present, they do not go through it with more coolness or steadiness than the whites.  They are more ardent after their female: but love seems with them to be more an eager desire, than a tender delicate mixture of sentiment and sensation. Their griefs are transient.  Those numberless afflictions, which render it doubtful whether heaven has given life to us in mercy or in wrath, are less felt, and sooner forgotten with them.  In general, their existence appears to participate more of sensation than reflection.  To this must be ascribed their disposition to sleep when abstracted from their diversions, and }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber210}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber210}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 unemployed in labour.  An animal whose body is at rest, and who does not reflect, must be disposed to sleep of course.  Comparing them by their faculties of memory, reason, and imagination, it appears to me, that in memory they are equal to the whites; in reason much inferior, as I think one could scarcely be found capable of tracing and }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *314}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  comprehending the investigations of Euclid; and that in imagination they are dull, tasteless, and anomalous. . . . But never yet could I find that a black had uttered a thought above the level of plain narration; never see even an elementary trait of painting or sculpture. . . . Misery is often the parent of the most affecting touches in poetry.--Among the blacks is misery enough, God knows, but no poetry.  Love is the peculiar oestrum of the poet.  Their love is ardent, but it kindles the senses only, not the imagination. }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     . . . It is not against experience to suppose, that different species of the same genus, or varieties of the same species, may possess different qualifications. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B660}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B660}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F660 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN660]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Will not a lover of natural history then, one who views the gradations in all the races of animals with the eye of philosophy, excuse an effort to keep those in the department of man as distinct as }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *315}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  nature has formed them?  This unfortunate difference of color, and perhaps of faculty, is a powerful obstacle to the emancipation of these people. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B661}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B661}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F661 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN661]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Jefferson's blindness to the situation is obvious to us now.  We can, from }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber211}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber211}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 our vantage, see the situation of slavery like we can see a gun to the head. But, in Jefferson's time, the situation was obscured by the more salient (and affirming) dispositions.  While arguing that white people were obviously more beautiful than blacks, Jefferson cites blacks' "own judgment in favour of the whites," }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B662}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B662}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F662 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN662]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  but does not see the extreme power disparities that likely lead to this perceived reaction.  This is an egregious instance of dispositions wrongly being thought to be "revealed" through behavior. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B663}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B663}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F663 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN663]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Jefferson does not see that the situation of forced labor might require the kind of palliative function of song that Douglass spoke of, }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B664}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B664}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F664 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN664]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  but rather concludes that the singing is evidence of a "carefree" disposition. Furthermore, he remarkably infers that blacks dispositionally required less sleep than whites, ignoring the fact that sleep was situationally less available to them. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B665}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B665}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F665 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN665]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Jefferson also concludes that blacks had inferior reason and imagination, without appreciating the situation--the fact that blacks were denied schooling, for example, or the opportunity for creative expression }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B666}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B666}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F666 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN666]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 --that created that condition. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B667}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B667}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F667 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN667]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  At the same time that blacks were perceived as inferior to whites in reason, they were seen as dispositionally superior to whites in doing }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *316}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  the sort of work that the slaveholders needed.  As Jefferson noted, they seemed to forget their afflictions, required less sleep, and were more resistant to heat.  Therefore, they were well-suited as forced laborers. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B668}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B668}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F668 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN668]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
}{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber212}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber212}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   It is important to note that Jefferson does not entirely disregard the influence of the situational effects of slavery.  In fact, he purports to examine and control for such evidence.  He explains that "[t]he improvement of the blacks in body and mind, in the first instance of their mixture with the whites, has been observed by every one, and proves that their inferiority is not the effect merely of their condition of life." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B669}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B669}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F669 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN669]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Jefferson continues his proof by comparing American slaves to Roman slaves, who he claims were treated significantly worse than American slaves--in other words, their situations were even more stifling. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B670}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B670}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F670 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN670]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   But, as he then claims, }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     notwithstanding these and other discouraging circumstances among the Romans, their slaves were often their rarest artists.  They excelled too in science, insomuch as to be usually employed as tutors to their master's children.  Epictetus, Terence, and Phaedrus, were slaves.  But they were of the race of whites.  It is not their condition then, but nature, which has produced the distinction. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B671}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B671}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F671 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN671]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *317}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Thomas Jefferson, who announced to the world that "all men are created equal," }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B672}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B672}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F672 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN672]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  who founded the University of Virginia and carried the Enlightenment's torch through his lifelong emphasis on the importance of education, who believed he was an objective natural historian and scientist, still could not see the situation in the case of slavery.  Dispositionism runs deep, and we can know with fair confidence that, were we living in Virginia at the time that Jefferson wrote, }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber213}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber213}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 our position likely would have been even less situationally sensitive than his was. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B673}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B673}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F673 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN673]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  A review of Jefferson's justifications highlights the source and destination of our dispositionist tendencies.  When we miss or downplay the situation, and see or exaggerate dispositions, we miss the hurdles, holes, quicksand, and other obstacles that can influence the outcome of any race, and instead attribute the outcomes to the racers themselves.  Given the existence of the fundamental attribution error, it is very hard for us not to assume that we are all competing on a level playing field, that the victor deserves the spoils and the losers deserve their fate.  And it is not just individuals that are engaged in a dispositional race.  Indeed, entire "races" are competing against each other.  The fact that one group dominates another often carries its own justification.  Superior races, as measured by their ability to dominate, should dominate, as nature appears to reveal. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B674}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B674}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F674 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN674]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   As Alabama physician Josiah Nott put it in 1854, }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *318}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  shortly before the Dred Scott decision: }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B675}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B675}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F675 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN675]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   "Nations and races, like individuals, have each an especial destiny: some are born to rule, and others to be ruled. . . . No two distinctly-marked races can dwell together on equal terms. . . . [H]uman progress has arisen mainly from the war of the races. . . ." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B676}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B676}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F676 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN676]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qc \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
}{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *319}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  ii. Consent--implied and revealed}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber214}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber214}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Those justifications led to another separate, but related, dispositionist justification of slavery--the myth that, were Africans competent to choose, they would choose slavery for themselves.  But because they were not, the responsibility fell on whites to choose for them.  George Fitzhugh, a slavery proponent and celebrated Southern polemicist wrote, "[the Negro] is but a grown up child, and must be governed as a child, not as a lunatic or criminal.  The master occupies towards him the place of parent or guardian." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B677}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B677}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F677 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN677]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Proponents argued that slavery was the best thing for the Africans because it allowed them to become "civilized," to become Christian, and to live a comfortable life, free from the dangers of their former life as African savages. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B678}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B678}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F678 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN678]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Thus, there was at least an implied consent on the part of blacks to the slavery system.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *320}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  A more extreme version of that paternalistic dispositionist fallacy was the view that slaves actually chose to be slaves--their consent and support for the institution was actually revealed by their happiness and satisfaction.  In this view, there was really nothing paternalistic involved. Slaves were perceived to have consented by the fact that they seemed to like it.  In this conception, slavery was contrasted with the system of wage labor in the North, and was seen as clearly superior.  Fitzhugh again made the argument: }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     The negro slaves of the South are the happiest, and, in some sense, the }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber215}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber215}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 freest people in the world.  The children and the aged and infirm work not at all, and yet have all the comforts and necessaries of life provided for them.  They enjoy liberty, because they are oppressed neither by care nor labor. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B679}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B679}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F679 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN679]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  In 1861, former United States Senator James Henry Hammond from South Carolina explained the seemingly unchallenged "logic" of the system: }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     "In all social systems there must be a class to do the menial duties, to perform the drudgery of life.  That is, a class requiring but a low order of intellect and but little skill.  Its requisites are vigor, docility, [and] fidelity.  Such a class you must have, or you would not have that other class which leads progress, civilization, and refinement.  It constitutes the very mudsill of society and of political government. . . . Fortunately for the South, she has found a race adapted to that purpose at her hand.  A race inferior to her own, but eminently qualified in temper, in vigor, in docility, in capacity to stand the climate, to answer all her purposes.  We use them for our purpose, and we call them slaves." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B680}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B680}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F680 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN680]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  From where Hammond stood, the need for slaves was beyond question.  That was the way great societies had always done it.  If you accept as a starting point that certain people are inherently and }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *321}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  dispositionally inferior, the best way to maximize the utility of society is to put those people at the bottom. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B681}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B681}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F681 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN681]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   And if it happens that even the slaves prefer--or would if }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber216}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber216}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 they were competent--to be slaves, then the idea of emancipation is ludicrous.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  b. Amplifying dispositionism: The anti-slavery bogeypeople}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  In addition to those dispositionist rationales, defenders of the status quo of slavery also pointed to threats of bogeymen lurking in any change to the situation.  Change was frightening, and could be made to seem even more so, not only to slaveholders, but to lower classes as well, including non-slaveholding planters and poor white laborers.  Each of these groups viewed the maintenance of the social system as essential to keeping their fears from becoming reality.  As historian James McPherson puts it, "[slaveholders] managed to }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *322}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  convince most non-slaveholding whites in the South (two-thirds of the white population there) that emancipation would produce economic ruin, social chaos, and racial war." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B682}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B682}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F682 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN682]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Even those that perhaps philosophically favored emancipation feared that, if blacks were released, hell might break loose.  For instance, in a particularly grave rendition of this concern, Thomas Jefferson predicted that }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     [d]eep rooted prejudices entertained by the whites; ten thousand recollections, by the blacks, of the injuries they have sustained; new provocations; the real distinctions which nature has made; and many other circumstances, will divide us into parties, and produce convulsions which will probably never end but in the extermination of the one or the other race. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B683}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B683}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F683 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN683]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *323}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Defenders of slavery pointed to what they saw as the }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber217}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber217}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 inevitable and total destruction of the fabric of Southern society if slavery was abolished.  As historian Eugene Genovese notes, "[t]he proslavery theorists never tired of proclaiming that the greatness of ancient Egypt, Israel, Greece, and Rome had been based on slavery . . . ." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B684}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B684}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F684 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN684]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   The defenders of slavery assumed that there could not be a great and prosperous society without slavery; they were unable to imagine something that differed from the status quo.  The only way to be prosperous, they believed, was the "proven" way, and thinking about alternatives was a dangerous endeavor.  Of course, the views that blacks were inferior, that a successful society depended on the social system of slavery, and that only chaos would ensue from changing it, were wrong.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  But the fear-mongering served an important purpose for those who engaged in it beyond simply predicting hypothetical future outcomes.  As we have hinted throughout this Article and as we will describe in more detail in other work, }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B685}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B685}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F685 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN685]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  there is considerable and growing social psychological research indicating that the presence of a threat to existing systems activates in us a general motive to justify or legitimate the system, as is. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B686}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B686}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F686 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN686]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   That research further reveals that one of the most effective means of legitimating the system is to dispositionalize those groups that might otherwise be seen as unjustly victimized.  By increasing fears that the system was at risk, and that any change to the system would be calamitous, the defenders of slavery were, }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber218}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber218}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 consciously or not, acting to reinforce the system and the dispositionism of slaves on which the system relied.  And they were likely having that effect on all groups, regardless of their relationship with the system of slavery, including those who were in fact being harmed.}\par 
\pard \qc \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
}{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *324}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  c. Dispositionalizing the opposition}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1   We have thus far explored several ways in which knowledge structures evolved to justify the institution of slavery on behalf of those who sought to legitimize it.  More specifically, we have emphasized how slaves--and all identity groups for that matter--were more or less dispositionalized in order to "make sense" of the systems of slavery, and to inoculate them with the "patina of consent." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B687}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B687}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F687 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN687]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   But the deep capture of "knowledge" is not accomplished without the deep capture of knowledge production, and that is also part of the unseen situation.  As was true during Galileo's struggles with the Catholic Church, as Stigler argued was true four decades ago of administrative regulators, and as we hypothesize is generally true today, conceptions of ourselves, others, and our institutions do not just emerge from bottom-up, individual analyses of the given facts.  Nor do they emerge from a fair tournament of ideas, in which the most meritorious ideas, beliefs, and knowledge structures win out.  Instead, the winners are created, promoted, subsidized, and protected by the systems, institutions, and individuals who }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber219}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber219}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 enjoy the greatest power to define the situation.  Influencing the interior situation means influencing, among other things, the information people have access to, how it is framed, and its credibility.  The success of pro-slavery dispositionism required that dynamic. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B688}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B688}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F688 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN688]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  In this subsection, we focus briefly on one of its many elements: dealing with competing ideas and criticisms of abolitionists.  Here was the problem.  Although dispositionalizing slaves helped many Southerners ease the dissonance they felt from not permitting the self-evident natural rights that they were preaching, it did not relieve the dissonance created by the emerging abolition movement.  Particularly after the Nat Turner rebellion in 1831, those who justified and endorsed slavery had to explain why so many other people were not persuaded by the force of their seemingly air-tight arguments.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  The dissonance was likely significant.  According to social psychologists, when such a conflict grows strong, something usually has to }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *325}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  give. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B689}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B689}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F689 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN689]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Of course, a person could reconsider and alter her own views, but that is a rare event, particularly when there is a lot at stake, as there was on the issue of slavery.  Research shows that an extremely common means of extinguishing that sort of interpersonal or intergroup dissonance is to attribute the gap between our outlook and someone else's to a lack of objectivity on their part.  We assume that there is some dispositional source of their bias--stupidity, or laziness, or corruption, or self-interest. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber220}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber220}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B690}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B690}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F690 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN690]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Again, dispositionism saves the day.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  And that is largely what happened in the South.  To defend slavery and the entire worldview on which it was based, slavery's proponents dismissed abolitionists and their ilk as ignorant, hypocritical, and jealous of the success achieved in the South.  As historian James McPherson summarizes: }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     [Slavery] also established the foundation for an upper class of gentlemen to cultivate the arts, literature, hospitality, and public service.  It created a far superior society to that of the "vulgar, contemptible, counter-jumping" Yankees. . . . "Instead of an evil," said John C. Calhoun in summing up the southern position, slavery was "a positive good . . . the most safe and stable basis for free institutions in the world." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B691}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B691}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F691 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN691]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Southern newspapers echoed this sentiment.  "'The great evil of Northern free society,"' insisted a South Carolina newspaper, "'is, that it is burdened with a servile class of MECHANICS and LABOURERS, unfit for self-government, yet clothed with the attributes and powers of citizens."' }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B692}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B692}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F692 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN692]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   A Georgia newspaper was even more emphatic in its distaste: }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     Free society!  we sicken at the name.  What is it but a conglomeration of greasy mechanics, filthy operatives, small-fisted farmers, and moon-}{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *326}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  struck theorists? . . .  The prevailing class one meets with [in the North] is that of mechanics struggling to be genteel, and small farmers who do their own drudgery, and yet are hardly fit for association with a southern }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber221}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber221}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 gentleman's body servant. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B693}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B693}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F693 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN693]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  In retrospect, such attacks on the dispositions of abolitionist enemies appear to be a fairly transparent tactic to discredit them.  At the time, however, those who offered the critiques and those who shared in them, undoubtedly believed that the attacks were a fairly neutral assessment of the truth.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  d. Our dispositionalization of slavery}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  In just that way, today, we look back with horror at slavery and the institutions, customs, laws, and mindsets that made it possible.  We express outrage that "those people" could have embraced such inappropriate dispositionist assumptions, when it is so clear, in hindsight, that those assumptions were not only wrong, but self-serving mechanisms of oppression.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  The same central lessons of the Galileo story are all evident here.  We retrospectively witness powerful groups abusing their power by creating and enforcing oppressive laws based on false, but self-serving, dispositionist attributions.  As with the Galileo story, we manage to dispositionalize the people involved as "evil"--and obviously different from us.  Yet, we are nonetheless confident that history is not repeating itself today, confident that we are not blinded too by some false dispositionism, confident that we are not also unduly missing the situation.  In the examples of Galileo and American slavery we can, in hindsight, see situation as palpably as we can see a gun to }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber222}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber222}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 the head.  And such a visible form of influence is, we all agree, unacceptable.  Because we can see the situation in retrospect, we can take comfort in the belief that we are not subject to anything similar and that, unlike those who advanced or participated in those oppressive practices or "bad acts," we are dispositionally "good."}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  But here is the rub.  Those are precisely the same dispositionist assumptions that the groups who we see as "bad" made about themselves.  They did not see oppressive power shaping their society.  We suspect further that we take comfort in our own outrage at these obvious evils of the past, comfort that helps convince us that we must not be missing anything like it in our own situation. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B694}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B694}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F694 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN694]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   The problem is }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *327}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  that we do not understand that the best defense against such patterns comes less from identifying flawed ideas than it does from identifying the flaws in those who construct the ideas.  The problem is in the human animal and our faith that we are immune to that which we generally neither see nor understand: the situation.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Indeed, instead of assuming that our current views about slavery and Galileo's imprisonment provide evidence that we will not again make such horrific errors, a more reasonable inference would be that those examples, and the countless others like them, constitute a compelling indication that history will continue to repeat--precisely because we do not appear to know what is moving it.  If humans are capable of believing that those we directly harm (be }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber223}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber223}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 they slaves, or Milgram's "learners") deserve their fate, it should be even easier to rationalize the harms imposed less directly, less saliently, and more situationally.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  3. Conclusion}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  We can thus see that the power of dispositionism, and the patterns to which it gives shape, are witnessed again and again not just in social psychology's attributional experiments, nor just in the mundane basic habits of our lives, but in large and central questions of social policy and human society.  We will not pursue this exegesis further here, but the basic pattern is becoming clear.  When we see disposition and miss situation, we implicitly presume that the situation is neutral, that the playing field is stable, and that everything else is equal.  We see outcomes, then, as dispositionally deserved.  When the system is challenged or threatened, all those involved in the system have a stake in reinforcing it and, thus, reinforcing its legitimating rationalizations.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  As this discussion has indicated, the institution of slavery emerged first and was justified later.  And the justifications came piecemeal as the need arose.  Jefferson's initial attempt to make sense of the institution was, at least by comparison to later efforts, quite tentative.  }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *328}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  By the middle of the nineteenth century, with the attacks on slavery growing to a feverish pitch, the institution's justifications were fully formed and robust.  And they }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber224}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber224}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 did the trick.  What had once been a "necessary evil" had been rendered a just, natural, and enviable path to civilized greatness.  And many in the South were proud of that transition.  South Carolina's Senator James H. Hammond spoke of earlier times when Southerners "'believed slavery to be an evil--weakness-- disgrace--nay a sin. . . . [I]n fear and trembling [they] awaited a doom that [they] deemed inevitable."' }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B695}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B695}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F695 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN695]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   But that belief was temporary, as was the resultant fear.  "'[A] few bold spirits took the question up; they compelled the South to investigate it anew and thoroughly, and what is the result?' [asked Hammond,] 'Why, it would be difficult to find a Southern man who feels the system to be the slightest burthen on his conscience."' }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B696}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B696}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F696 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN696]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Hammond's fellow South Carolinian, John C. Calhoun, recounted the same history from dissonance to resonance as follows: "Many in the South once believed that [slavery] was a moral and political evil; that folly and delusion are gone; we see it now in its true light, and regard it as the most safe and stable basis for free institutions in the world." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B697}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B697}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F697 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN697]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   And so it is that visible evil fades into the situation and, with it, becomes invisible.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
D. The Situational Bogeypeople}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  If not before, it is usually at this point in the presentation of our ideas to friends, family, students, and colleagues that we are stopped with one or another version of "I hear what you are saying and I may even agree, but I }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber225}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber225}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 think you are going too far.  Is it not dangerous to take the situation so seriously?"}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  We suspect that many of our readers may be experiencing similar reactions, and we understand the concern.  To continue our argument, then, we think it is necessary to directly engage several versions of this kind of reaction to our claims.  We are doing so not only to try to mollify our readers' worries, but also because these common reactions harmfully narrow the boundaries of most social and political debates in our society today.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *329}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  One of our main concerns with those arguments is that they are not always what they purport to be.  In our experience, they are not offered as a concern that emerges once the power of the situation is fully recognized.  Rather, they are implication-based fears that prevent people from truly understanding the nature of our argument--that is, of the situation. Still, those responses are routine, usually as a fallback position--a final trump card.  So we will do our best in this Section to respond to commonly held intuitions, which we call situational bogeypeople--siblings of those that we encountered earlier. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B698}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B698}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F698 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN698]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   These intuitions seem to come in several varieties.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  1. The Communism Bogeyman}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  The most popular version of the challenge goes like this: }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     The playing field is level.  And, as long as everyone is starting the race }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber226}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber226}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 together, there is no reason to be concerned about the fact that there will be some winners and some losers.  That's what a fair competition is designed to do: separate winners from losers as it creates incentives to win in the process.  Equality of opportunity does not guarantee equality of outcome.  If policymakers were to begin looking to outcomes as a measure of opportunity, they would transform our free world into a communist or socialist regime.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  A major weakness of this challenge is that it is not actually a response to, as much as it is a denial of, our point.  Our claim that situational influences benefit some groups and disadvantage others is a claim that the playing field is, in ways unseen, not level and that we are all operating under the wrong presumption.  To assert that the playing field is level may, in fact, confirm our point: people do not see relevant situational influences (which would include many features of the playing field) and overattribute outcomes to dispositions.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  That basic challenge sometimes finds some reinforcement, though, by retreating to the following version of the communist bogeyman: }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     Even if the playing field is not perfectly level, it is level enough for us to attribute success or failure to the participants' dispositions.  After all, many people who appear to start with situational disadvantages outrun those who appear to begin with situational advantages--simply because they were dispositionally inclined to overcome those disadvantages. }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *330}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  This }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber227}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber227}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 response is just a more nuanced form of denial.  Acknowledging trivial unevenness on the playing field can often be a disarmingly effective means of justifying ignoring that unevenness.  Of course, it is possible that the field is only trivially uneven, but the evidence typically adduced for that claim tends to be very thin and seems to be based more on shared intuition than situational sensitivity.  We do not want to deny that Horatio Alger, and many like him, have successfully managed to turn adversity into opportunity-- or, in other words, have dispositionally chosen to overcome significant situational opposition.  Nor do we want to deny that the hope of just such an outcome is inspiring for many poor and hard-working people in our society. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B699}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B699}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F699 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN699]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   But neither do we believe that such exceptional success stories are much more than that--exceptional.  The fact that there is some movement across socioeconomic groups does not imply that situation does not immensely affect outcomes. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B700}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B700}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F700 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN700]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  First, when members of disadvantaged groups compete against advantaged groups, the situation will influence the outcome even if there are exceptions.  An extremely fast and driven runner with a brick tied to his foot may well outpace a slower, unencumbered runner.  But a class of brick-laden runners will tend to seem plodding or malingering as they fall behind their brick-free competitors.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Moreover, what may be true individually almost certainly cannot be true }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber228}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber228}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 generally.  For instance, the fact that some hard-working people manage to climb out of poverty does not mean that all could, if only they worked as hard.  The point about a competitive race is, }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *331}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  after all, to separate winners from losers.  The situation of the competition creates a meaningful limit to the number of winners.  If everyone ran as hard as Horatio Alger, the speed of the race would increase to be sure, but the number of winners and losers would not. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B701}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B701}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F701 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN701]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  In any event, the claim that policymakers should not look to outcomes to help determine if there is a problem with the playing field simply denies a major feature of our argument.  Because the playing field is part of the situation, there is little reason to be confident that we can know when it is level and fair.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Recall that nobody believed that the teachers in Milgram's experiment would shock the learners all the way up to 450 volts. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B702}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B702}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F702 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN702]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   The fact that two-thirds of them did suggests that even the experts, including Milgram, misperceived the power of the situation and overestimated the role of disposition.  What social psychology and history teach us is not to trust our perceptions, but to doubt them.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Of course, claiming that we should learn from outcomes is a very different claim than "from each according to his ability, to each according to his needs [.]" }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B703}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B703}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F703 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN703]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Our argument is not that we should all finish the race }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber229}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber229}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 together, but that where people finish may reveal more about the race than it reveals about the racers.  Outcomes can serve an immensely valuable evidentiary role in any serious attempt to ensure that the playing field is level.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Moreover, the deference to outcomes as a measure of the process is nothing new.  Indeed, it was Stigler who introduced that very methodology in assessing whether regulations were serving their purported goal of advancing the public interest.  This outcome-based }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *332}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  assessment, as we indicated above, is one of the most important foundational insights of conventional economic theory. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B704}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B704}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F704 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN704]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Finally, the idea that taking situation into account will somehow reduce the incentives of the situationally disadvantaged to try to win, strikes us as counterintuitive and contrary to the most basic assumptions of those who promote free competition.  If, in fact, the playing field is uneven, it seems that all competitors gain, not lose, incentive to run faster by leveling the field.  Those who are disadvantaged on the current field will be given a fair chance, and those who are advantaged will be given a meaningful challenge. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B705}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B705}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F705 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN705]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  2. The Personal-Responsibility Bogeyman}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  A second popular version of the situational bogeyman goes like this: }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     If we begin to take situation into account, people will no longer be held personally responsible for their actions.  Criminals will be able to blame }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber230}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber230}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 almost anything they do on the fact that they had a bad situation.  "It wasn't me, it was the situation; I'm a victim of circumstances" will be heard in all the courts of the land and criminals will run free.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  We have several responses to this bogeyman.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  First, as we summarized above, the law already takes situation into account, through doctrines like duress in contract, }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B706}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B706}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F706 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN706]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  necessity in trespass, and "heat of passion" }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B707}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B707}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F707 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN707]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  in criminal law. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B708}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B708}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F708 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN708]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   The problem, as we see it, is that the situation is far from being an occasional, glaringly obvious gun to the head, as the current law treats it.  It is a }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *333}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  force of greater or lesser magnitude in nearly every human interaction.  When we argue that the law must take situation into account, we are asking the law to continue to function as it always has, but in a way that gives the situation the weight that social science demonstrates it possesses in human affairs.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Second, there is a strong element of stereotype in the account of this bogeyman.  The stereotype is that the situational character--our model of the human animal--is a puppet on the strings of the situation, entirely lacking in disposition or volition.  But this is a false picture of our model.  We fully agree that humans possess dispositions and that dispositions likely play some role in a great portion of our behavior.  But, as we argue above, current legal theory and the law overestimate the point at which disposition ends and the situation begins.  No one wants criminals to run free, but at the same time, we }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber231}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber231}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 do not want to lay blame where it is not due.  A law that takes a nuanced view of the roles of situation and disposition will be better able to correctly assign dispositional responsibility and blame where they belong.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Nevertheless, it might seem that, if the law were to expand its acknowledgement of situational factors, the result would be to expand the avenues for evading responsibility.  Far from it.  As we have shown, people systematically--and often quite erroneously--attribute causation, responsibility, and blame to the most visible actors in a given situation. They compound their mistakes through the fundamental attribution error, by assuming that action is attributable to disposition, rather than situation. Judges, juries, and legislators are as vulnerable to these cognitive biases as anyone else.  If we are truly committed to the principle of personal responsibility, then we should be deeply troubled by the prospect that we are applying it without taking these biases into account.  For the damages to fit the tort or the punishment to fit the crime, we must first be sensitive to the situation.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  It is our contention that, by ignoring situation, we may be ignoring the true role of disposition and letting those actors who are most responsible for the harms we seek to redress off the hook.  To better illustrate this point, we offer a thought experiment, a variation on an actual experiment. Imagine an alternate world in which Stanley Milgram is actually interested in }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber232}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber232}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 studying the effects of negative reinforcement on learning.  Having seen the power of the situation, he designs an experiment identical in every respect to the actual one, with one difference: the learner receives real electric }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *334}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  shocks.  Unfortunately, when Milgram runs these experiments, the learner receives third-degree burns and sues for damages.  Who should be held responsible?}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Under commonly held notions of "personal responsibility," some might blame the learner.  He was an adult and ought to have known what he was getting into.  After all, everyone knows that electricity is hot!  Therefore, he should be made to deal with the consequences of his decision, instead of looking to blame others for them.  Some people, also citing "personal responsibility," might blame the teacher who flipped the switches because she had many opportunities to stop.  There were teachers who refused to go along with the experiment when they saw the learner's suffering; no one held a gun to this teacher's head.  Shouldn't she be responsible for the (quite visible) consequences of her actions?}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  A typical "personal responsibility" view of this lawsuit would likely stop at that analysis in either allowing the loss or imposing liability.  But what of Stanley Milgram?  Shouldn't he have known of the risks to the learner? Shouldn't he be held "personally responsible" for setting up a situation in which the teacher was quite likely to flip the switches?  Or perhaps Yale }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber233}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber233}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 University should be held responsible for not better monitoring Milgram. Milgram apparently conducted his original experiments with the university's knowledge and may have been motivated by the university's tenure standards to perform this sort of research.  Doesn't Yale profit, even to this day, from the attention garnered by Milgram's work?}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  If any part of this account conflicts with your intuitions, then consider the famed McDonald's coffee case of a few years ago. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B709}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B709}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F709 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN709]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   In that case, hot coffee spilled on Stella Liebeck's lap, giving her third-degree burns. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B710}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B710}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F710 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN710]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   When she won a verdict against McDonald's, Liebeck became a symbol of the law's role in absolving citizens of personal responsibility and the poster child for tort reform. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B711}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B711}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F711 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN711]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   "[R]adio talk-show hosts around the country . . . lambasted the plaintiff, her attorneys and the jurors on air. Declining to be interviewed[,] . . . one juror explained that he already had received }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *335}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  angry calls from citizens around the country." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B712}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B712}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F712 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN712]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Under the common sense "personal responsibility" view, Ms. Liebeck was responsible for knowing the coffee was hot and ought to have been more careful in handling it.  After all, "she spilled it on herself." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B713}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B713}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F713 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN713]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   However, when the jurors were forced to look at the situation, they were able to see that McDonald's shared responsibility for the burns. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B714}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B714}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F714 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN714]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  We present this case and our hypothetical to make clear that the term "personal responsibility" does not resolve difficult questions of fault. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber234}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber234}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 It merely begs them.  Our point is not that people should never be held responsible for their acts, but that one should not assume that their "common sense" can be trusted to assign responsibility. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B715}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B715}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F715 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN715]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   The law must be concerned with questions of situation.  }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *336}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  How much does the situation influence individuals?  Who controls and profits from particular situations? How might the situation be altered to influence individuals in other ways? These are not easy questions, but to avoid them may be to encourage personal irresponsibility.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Put differently, the concern that taking hard-to-see situation into account may "encourage criminals to run freely through our streets" ignores the less visible possibility that disregarding situation may encourage even more.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  3. The Paternalism Bogeyman}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  No contingent of bogeypeople would be complete without the paternalism bogeyman.  Unlike the prior bogeypeople, the figure of paternalism appears more prominently and openly in legal theoretic discourse.  Although its precise definition often remains shrouded in mystery, that has not stopped it from exercising a powerful influence in legal-theoretic debate. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B716}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B716}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F716 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN716]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Generations of theorists have agreed that paternalism is no friend of the dispositional human actor presiding at the core of the traditional liberal picture.  John Stuart Mill, who early laid down the line against paternalism in a "civilized" society, stated that, "the only purpose for which power can be }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber235}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber235}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 rightfully exercised over any member of a civilized community, against his will, is to prevent harm to others.  His own good, either physical or moral, is not a sufficient warrant." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B717}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B717}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F717 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN717]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Professor David Shapiro, in his famous article on the subject, claimed that the concept of paternalism can be conceived of in a number of weaker or stronger formulations. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B718}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B718}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F718 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN718]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   But the basic anti-paternalism suspicion has, by now, attached to almost any version of it.  In his article, Shapiro set out, in part, to challenge Duncan Kennedy's seminal claim that paternalism was actually quite widespread in private and public social arrangements, including, importantly, many }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *337}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  areas of the law. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B719}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B719}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F719 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN719]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Shapiro gave a renewed voice to the traditional view of paternalism as showstopper, arguing that legal justifications for many of the kinds of arrangements Kennedy had pointed to were actually well grounded in anti-paternalism (at least rhetorically). }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B720}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B720}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F720 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN720]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Professor Shapiro claimed that, in fact, "anti-paternalism (which [we] should perhaps . . . [be] calling 'pro-autonomy') is a dominant strain in our tradition." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B721}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B721}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F721 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN721]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Moreover, as we have already indicated, legal economists, when met with claims they perceive as threatening to individual autonomy, are quick to retreat behind, not economics per se, but an anti-paternalistic defense of individual freedom. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B722}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B722}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F722 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN722]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Much of the most recent law and economics-oriented scholarship on paternalism has been directed at defining the boundaries and types of paternalistic social policies that can }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber236}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber236}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 be justified, assuming that strong deference should be given to the basic "libertarian" view of individual autonomy. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B723}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B723}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F723 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN723]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   The paternalism bogeyman, despite the efforts of Kennedy and others, reigns.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *338}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  A central effect of its reign is to scare away potential interventions in the apparent dispositional choices of individuals or arguments that would put the meaning of such choices into doubt.  To do so, the paternalism bogeyman patronizes the dispositional actor by highlighting only the most salient kinds of situational exercises of power over individuals, calling these paternalism, and demanding they yield in the name of the freedom that is assumed otherwise to govern.  In this way, the paternalism bogeyman, like the others, succeeds against our argument only by denying what social science teaches (and markets reveal) about the power of the unseen situation.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Shapiro, for example, provides a vivid but profoundly dispositionist picture when he "lay[s] out some baselines" for the study of paternalism. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B724}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B724}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F724 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN724]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Adopting the axiom of "consent" as central to the analysis, Shapiro discerns the quintessential form of what he and most theorists find to be a permissible kind of paternalism --self-paternalism. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B725}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B725}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F725 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN725]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   The guiding figure here is Odysseus, that hero of the disposition human journey, binding himself to the mast of his ship as it passes by the Sirens, and instructing his crew that they should not untie him no matter how vigorously he demands to be unbound. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B726}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B726}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F726 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN726]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Odysseus fears his future-self will, if set free, choose to stay }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber237}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber237}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 forever among the beautiful, seductive voices of the Sirens. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B727}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B727}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F727 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN727]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   In contrast to this permissible "baseline" of self-paternalism is an even more vivid dispositionist vision of the sinister paternalism bogeyman--the Grand Inquisitor: }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     [T]he case for a claim of weak paternalism is itself weakened . . . when the asserted incapacity exists on a question of basic values or assumptions, especially (but not exclusively) when those values or assumptions are shared by a large group of mature adults.  The Grand Inquisitor who is convinced that the souls of the heretics can be saved only if they are coerced into recanting their heresy may see the case as the quintessence of weak paternalism.  But I do not. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B728}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B728}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F728 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN728]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Shapiro accepts as a premise that power can be exercised to alter people's opinions even on "basic assumptions," but this power is pictured as a salient external power, in the figure of the Grand }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *339}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Inquisitor. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B729}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B729}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F729 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN729]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   The possibility that power is exercised in unseen ways over "basic assumptions" is not even imagined; and the charge of paternalism becomes a bulwark against examining the power operating in the formation of those assumptions.  If paternalism is a troublesome exercise of power when implemented through salient situational influences, then critical realism suggests that we ought to begin our analysis at exactly the place where Shapiro places the bogeyman's barricades.  Put differently, if our ambition is to foster a world in which }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber238}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber238}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 people are encouraged to act according to their values, attitudes, and assumptions, then legal analysts need to look far deeper than just the obvious tip of the situational iceberg.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Further examination reveals that Shapiro's conventional "baselines" are the product not of analysis or theory, but of the fundamental attribution error.  Defending his decision to "embrace the anti-paternalist position," }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B730}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B730}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F730 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN730]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Shapiro falls back, as do so many, on intuitions and common sense perceptions: "on so basic a question of human relations I am not sure how feasible it is to do more than chart my own course." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B731}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B731}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F731 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN731]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Indeed, most defenders of anti-paternalism, Shapiro admits, have offered weak justification for their urge "to defend freedom against its critics." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B732}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B732}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F732 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN732]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   In charting such a course, Shapiro argues, "[e]ventually, a leap of faith is inevitable." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B733}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B733}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F733 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN733]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   In addition, the stakes in this leap are profoundly important, for "under prevailing community standards, the paternalist has the burden of persuasion." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B734}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B734}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F734 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN734]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  The problem, of course, is that the prevailing community standards reflect a fundamental flaw in human attributions, a flaw that appears to be greatly encouraged and enhanced by those who can best influence our situation.  Thus, in the name of avoiding obvious (that is, paternalistic) influences on people's choices, we may be turning ourselves over to less obvious, but no less powerful, influences.  Or, put slightly differently, in the name of protecting }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber239}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber239}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 dispositionism from }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *340}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  blatant situational threats, we may be unleashing hidden, but deeply captured, situational forces that leave us feeling as though we chose our lot.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Our purpose here is not to propose or defend a strong form of paternalism.  Indeed, we think our argument would demand a thorough reconceptualization of such conventional categories (strong-form paternalism, weak-form paternalism, self-paternalism, and so on) before such a discussion could be fruitful.  What we are arguing is that the charge of paternalism, as it is typically made, is an inadequate response to the claims we have presented.  What we propose is a more realistic exploration, and acceptance, of the powerful situational influences over human behavior that go far beyond the ropes of Odysseus and the fires of the Grand Inquisitor.  When we yield in our inquiries to the paternalism bogeyman, we may be yielding to basic assumptions that are themselves contestable and the subject of powerful situational influences.  The problem of paternalism is profound, but it cannot be answered with the conventional bogeyman response.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  4. Summary: The Bogeypeople as Response to, and Creation of, Threat }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     Some of the owner men were kind because they hated what they had to do, and some of them were angry because they hated to be cruel, and some of them were cold because they had long ago found that one could not be an owner unless one were cold. And all of them were caught in something larger than }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber240}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber240}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 themselves. Some of them hated the mathematics that drove them, and some were afraid, and some worshipped the mathematics because it provided a refuge from thought and from feeling . . . .--John Steinbeck }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B735}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B735}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F735 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN735]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Although there are others, }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B736}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B736}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F736 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN736]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  the previous Sections provide a fair sample of the bogeypeople.  We are less interested in providing a full }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *341}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  catalogue of the beasts than we are in understanding what motivates them.  People invoking the bogeypeople often begin by claiming to concede that the situation can have an immense, unseen effect on people's conduct.  They then follow that concession with a general "so what?" or, more specifically, with the invoking of one or more of the bogeypeople to make their case that it is better to pay no more attention to the situation than people already do.  Upon closer inspection, however, this technique of responding is better seen as a disarming means of denying our basic argument about the power of the situation.  It is not surprising that our audience would tend to disbelieve our claims.  Indeed, it is to be expected--just as it is easy to understand why so many people initially found Galileo's claims to be fanciful.  Without the telescope, it was one person's claim against the obvious.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  We do not believe that our arguments are immune to critique.  We strongly suspect that they are in many ways flawed.  But our worry and our experience is that they are not given a chance largely because people reject them because they are hard to see, and, more importantly, because they do not }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber241}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber241}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 want to see them.  The specter of the bogeypeople provides a mechanism for evading the situation.  Indeed, we suspect that one major reason for the success of neoclassical economics and disposition-driven theories of law is not simply that they are good for business, but also that they serve to protect us all from the disquieting possibilities that many of our basic systems are both harmful and rigged.  With that possibility in mind, it is illuminating to consider Milgram's career.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  After revealing, to his own surprise, the power of the unseen situation, Milgram's findings spawned an enormous hullabaloo.  In the words of Thomas Blass, "more than any other research in social psychology, the obedience experiments have been embroiled from the beginning in a number of controversies in which they have played a central and enriching role.  These include the ethics of research, the social psychology of the psychological experiment, and the deception versus role-playing controversy." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B737}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B737}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F737 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN737]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   It seems likely that much of the criticism found its source in the threat that Milgram's results posed to the notion that these systems are just.  To defend against that threat, Milgram's work had to be denied, challenged, and minimized in any way possible. }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *342}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  The upset generated by a Milgram . . . in part stems from ethical concerns.  But another part of [his experiments'] power lies precisely in their demonstration of how strong situational determinants are in shaping }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber242}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber242}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 behavior.  No resort to a correlation between 'those' people who do 'evil' things is allowed: the subjects were randomly assigned. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B738}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B738}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F738 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN738]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Despite his profound influence on psychology and the importance of his work to the fields of philosophy, political science, and education, Milgram was never granted tenure at Harvard. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B739}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B739}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F739 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN739]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   As Blass suggests, "[s]ome of the opposition toward Milgram came from colleagues who felt uneasy about him, ascribing to him certain negative properties of the obedience experiment." }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B740}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B740}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F740 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN740]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Focusing on Milgram's protocol may well have been a cover for a deeper uneasiness about his findings, as well as, a means of de-legitimating his work and, more importantly, legitimating our world.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  There is another, perhaps more telling, means of demonstrating that those who conjure the bogeypeople are, perhaps unconsciously, denying or minimizing our claim.  Consider the likely reaction to our argument if we were describing more visible, salient, and obvious forms of situational constraints.  Suppose, for example, that we were writing about antebellum slavery.  It does not seem controversial to argue, as we did, that slavery placed an immense and unjust situational constraint on slaves, or that slaves' conduct--including their singing--did not reveal dispositional consent to their fate.  We do not believe that the situational bogeypeople would be invoked in response to those claims. Nobody would accuse us of being communists for arguing that the situation of slaves should be taken seriously or that slavery should be abolished.  There is }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber243}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber243}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 no tendency to invoke the communist bogeyman in that context because, in retrospect, the situational constraints that caused the unequal outcomes are clear.  If we truly accept the idea that the situation wields a commanding influence, then the idea of attending to that influence seems obvious and unobjectionable.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Similarly, the personal-responsibility bogeyman remains dormant when the situation is slavery.  It should be remembered that slaves exercised some freedom under slavery: they developed their own }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *343}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  cultural patterns and practices; they found or created items of value to trade and sometimes earned money to buy things; they negotiated in various ways with their masters for, among other things, freedom upon their master's death; they plotted and executed escapes; and in some circumstances they bought their own freedom. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B741}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B741}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F741 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN741]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   So, while slaves undoubtedly operated under severe situational constraints, they were not without recourse to influence their own lives. There was room for disposition, and it undoubtedly played a role in their experiences.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Yet nobody today would claim that slaves should have taken personal responsibility for the conditions in which they lived.  Frederick Douglass, among others, bought his own freedom, and yet we do not blame those who did not for their predicament.  In such cases, the situation is obvious, and personal responsibility lies less with those enslaved by it, and more with those who }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber244}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber244}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 created it.  Placing personal responsibility on the slave is offensive.  When, on the other hand, the situation plays a significant role in the lives and conditions of those who enjoy "freedom" (here defined as "not slaves"), invocations of Horatio Alger and the personal responsibility bogeymen emerge. If we recognized the full sweep of the situational influences over our lives, we might be more hesitant with the charge of "personal responsibility," and the emergence of this bogeyman might be less automatic. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B742}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B742}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F742 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN742]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }\par 
\pard \qc \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
}{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *344}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  Conclusion: Facing our Fears}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     "It may be that we are puppets--puppets controlled by the strings of society.  But at least we are puppets with perception, with awareness.  And perhaps our awareness is the first step to our liberation."}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  --Stanley Milgram }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B743}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B743}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F743 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN743]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     Man is the only government-making animal in the world. }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     --Frederick Douglass }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B744}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B744}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F744 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN744]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     We all got to figure.  There's some way to stop this.  It's not like lightning or earthquakes.  We've got a bad thing made by men, and by God that's something we can change. }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     --John Steinbeck }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B745}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B745}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F745 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN745]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     The inferno of the living is not something that will be; if there is one, it is what is already here, the inferno that we live every day, that we form }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber245}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber245}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 by being together.  There are two ways to escape suffering it.  The first is easy for many: accept the inferno and become such a part of it that you can no longer see it.  The second is risky and demands constant vigilance and apprehension: seek and learn to recognize who and what, in the midst of the inferno, are not inferno, then make them endure, give them space.' }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1     --Italo Calvino }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B746}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B746}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F746 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN746]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   We understand that there is reason to be frightened and to feel threatened.  In fact, that is our point.  There is much at stake.  But to thwart the real dangers of the situation--the vulnerability to manipulation, the complex legal, social, ethical, and personal problems that it raises--we should look beyond the bogeypeople and face our fears.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  The goal of this Article is to encourage us to take seriously the situation.  We, and we hope others, will say more in future work about its implications.  Regardless, the most important implication }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *345}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  should be evident: there is not going to be a salient, simple policy solution to our predicament.  The belief or hope that such solutions exist is a manifestation of the problem--seeing a tiny portion of what is moving us and assuming that nothing else does.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  The problem is akin to another problem that is easier to imagine.  Who was responsible for slavery in this country?  Clearly, it was not the slaves. Their situation was too vividly powerful--like a gun to the head--to conclude }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber246}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber246}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 otherwise.  The most obvious answer is the slavemaster, and for good reason. Slavemasters bought and sold slaves, controlled slaves' environments, and dictated--often using brutal force--much of the slaves' conduct. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B747}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B747}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F747 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN747]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  There is more, however, to the situation than just the most prominent actors. Slavery was, among other things, a social system--a powerful situation--that was larger than both the slaves and the masters.  Slavery was a highly profitable industry, not only for the South, but also for the North, where textile mills, for example, relied on the availability of cheap cotton.  A plantation owner who freed his slaves would not only lose the economic value of his chattel but also the ability to produce his crops profitably.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Moreover, freeing slaves was illegal in some states and highly discouraged by social norms and conventions in all slave states. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B748}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B748}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F748 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN748]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   In that and countless other ways, the laws and the customs that slave owners lived under were highly constraining.  But those situational constraints were not, any more than the others, a natural, inevitable, or even random circumstance.  The situation was itself the consequence of a profitable economic system that created institutions and individuals with an interest in maintaining it.}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  As we have described, slave owners held situationally influenced "knowledge" and beliefs that also acted to reinforce the system and justify their place in it as powerful as the economic and social forces that they faced.  As we indicated above, a freed slave was, by some accounts, unhappy.  If a freed }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber247}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber247}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 African slave could not function outside of the paternalistic protection of the "peculiar institution," or if they would almost certainly be kidnapped and sold again into slavery and perhaps down the river, or if, at best, "freedom" meant laboring in the North where the working conditions were far worse, how could a plantation owner--even a "social welfare-maximizing" plantation owner-- justify freeing his slaves?  Furthermore, if }{\f1 \fs20 \b \cf1 *346}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1  slaveowners faced the threat that without slavery their society would not prosper and evolve, then the emancipation of slaves might come at a cost to freedom. }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_B749}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_B749}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_F749 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN749]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1   In short, slaves were not the only people who were subject to powerful situational influences.  Slaves, their owners, and their shared society, were all deeply captured.  So, who do we blame?}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  The point is that this may be the wrong question.  Suppose we were given the task of developing a means of emancipating African Americans from slavery and the many situational chains that have hindered them since.  Suppose that we had to accomplish that end without the horrors and shame of the Civil War, of Reconstruction, of Jim Crow, of segregation, and of disparate opportunities and outcomes that remain with us.  What would we do?}\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1 {\pard \par }
  Whatever our answer, it won't be simple, and it will require gaining a better understanding of the situation.}\par 
