}{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzSDUNumber324}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzSDUNumber324}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\*\bkmkstart Document1zzFN_F289}\f1 \fs20 {\*\bkmkend Document1zzFN_F289}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 }{\field {\*\fldinst {HYPERLINK \\l Document1zzFN_B289 }}{\fldrslt {\f1 \fs20 \ul \cf2 [FN289]}}}{\f1 \fs20 \cf1 . Galileo wrote of Copernicus' dedication to realism: }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1   And so he began to investigate what the system of the world could really be in nature, no longer for the sole convenience of the pure astronomer, whose calculations he had complied with, but in order to come to an understanding of such a noble physical problem; he was confident that, if one had been able to account for mere appearances by means of hypotheses which are not true, this could be done much better by means of the true and physical constitution of the world. }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Galileo's Considerations on the Copernican Opinion (1615), in The Galileo Affair, supra note 234, at 70, 74 (1989).}\par 
