\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1   "Every fact-pattern of common life, so far as the legal order can take it in, carries within itself its appropriate, natural rules, its right law.  This is a natural law which is real, not imaginary; it is not a creature of mere reason, but rests on the solid foundation of what reason can recognize in the nature of man and of the life conditions of the time and place; it is thus not eternal nor changeless nor everywhere the same, but is indwelling in the very circumstances of life.  The highest task of law-giving consists in uncovering and implementing this immanent law." }\par 
\pard \qj \fi0 \li0 \ri0 {\f1 \fs20 \cf1   Id. at 122 (quoting Levin Goldschmidt, Der Entwurf eines Handelgesetzbuchs f\uc0 \u252 r die Preussischen Staaten [Draft Trade Code for the Prussian States], pt. 2, reprinted in 4 Kritische Zeitschrift f\uc0 \u252 r die Gesammte Rechtswissenschaft 289 (Dernburg et al. eds., Heidelberg, Bangel & Schmitt 1857)).}\par 
